data: {"type":"layer1","modelId":"local/apple-fm","model":"Crucible (offline)","text":"## Zod Schema for IPv4 Address Validation\n\n```zod\ntype ipv4 = string\n\n{\n  \"type\": \"object\",\n  \"properties\": {\n    \"ip\": {\n      \"type\": \"string\",\n      \"pattern\": \"^(25[0-5]|2[0-4][0-9]|[01]?[0-9][0-9]?)\\.(25[0-5]|2[0-4][0-9]|[01]?[0-9][0-9]?)\\.(25[0-5]|2[0-4][0-9]|[01]?[0-9][0-9]?)\\.(25[0-5]|2[0-4][0-9]|[01]?[0-9][0-9]?)$\"\n    }\n  },\n  \"required\": [\"ip\"]\n}\n```\n\n## Explanation\n\nThis Zod schema defines an `ipv4` type, which represents an IPv4 address. The schema includes a single property, `ip`, which must be a string. The `pattern` property specifies the valid format for an IPv4 address, ensuring it consists of four octets separated by dots. Each octet must be a number between 0 and 255, and the octets cannot contain leading zeros unless the octet itself is zero.\n\n## Validation\n\nTo validate an IPv4 address using this schema, you can use the `vee-validate` package. Here's an example of how to validate an IPv4 address with the `vee-validate` package:\n\n```javascript\nconst veeValidator = require('vee-validate');\nconst { toTypedSchema } = require('@vee-validate/zod');\n\nconst schema = toTypedSchema({\n  type: 'object',\n  properties: {\n    ip: {\n      type: 'string',\n      pattern: '^(25[0-5]|2[0-4][0-9]|[01]?[0-9][0-9]?)\\.(25[0-5]|2[0-4][0-9]|[01]?[0-9][0-9]?)\\.(25[0-5]|2[0-4][0-9]|[01]?[0-9][0-9]?)\\.(25[0-5]|2[0-4][0-9]|[01]?[0-9][0-9]?)$'\n    }\n  },\n  required: ['ip']\n});\n\nconst validator = veeValidator.create({ schema });\n\nconst address = '192.168.1.1';\n\nconsole.log(validator.validate(address));\n```\n\nThis code snippet demonstrates how to validate an IPv4 address using the `vee-validate` package. The `veeValidator` package is used to create a validation schema, and the `toTypedSchema` function is used to convert the Zod schema into a format that can be understood by the `vee-validate` package. The `veeValidator.create` function is then used to create a validation instance, and the `validate` method is used to validate the IPv4 address.","done":true}

